    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-09-30T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-09-30T15:00:00-05:00" n="700"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d700">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 832.85/92b</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MEV1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgan</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-09-30T16:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 30, 1918, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department just advised that French representative on Allied Maritime Transport
                    Council sitting in London made suggestion <pb facs="0820" n="728"
                        xml:id="pg_728"/> about three weeks ago to Council that French
                    representatives at Rio be permitted to negotiate in behalf of the Council for
                    charter of remaining German boats interned in Brazil. American representatives
                    cabled to Shipping Board asking for instructions and Shipping Board, without the
                    knowledge of the Department, cabled through the Navy Department authorizing
                    American representatives on Council to acquiesce in plan proposed by French.</p>
                <p>As soon as this information was given to Department, Department insisted that
                    Shipping Board cancel its authorization to its representatives on Council and
                    that British and French also instruct their representatives not to proceed
                    further with arrangement.</p>
                <p>Department’s action was taken because negotiations which have been in progress in
                    Washington with respect to economic situation in Brazil are now coming to a
                    satisfactory conclusion and these ships have always been considered as part and
                    parcel of these negotiations.</p>
                <p>The above is for your confidential information and you are instructed to intimate
                    to the proper Brazilian authorities that this Government would not look with
                    favor on any transaction by which the disposition of these ships was taken out
                    of the conferences now being held in Washington which were instituted and
                    conducted with the full consent of Great Britain, France, Italy, Brazil and the
                    United States. It is unnecessary for you to mention this matter to your French
                    colleague.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
